    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-10-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-10-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="703"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d703">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.00111 <hi rend="superscript">Armament
                        Control/Military Secrets</hi>/2189</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Chief of the Division of Controls</hi>
                        (<persName corresp="#p_GJC1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Green</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-10-09">October 9,
                            1939</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_GWF1">William Francis Gibbs</persName>, of Gibbs &amp;
                    Cox, Inc., naval architects, called me by telephone this morning. He referred to
                    the Department’s letter of October 3 in regard to the proposed construction of
                    vessels of war in this country for the U. S. S. R. and said that he intended to
                    send a copy of that letter to the Soviet Naval Commission.<note n="10"
                        xml:id="d703fn10">A copy of the Department’s letter was sent by Gibbs and
                        Cox, Inc., to the Soviet Naval Mission and the Amtorg Trading Corporation,
                        New York, on October 9, 1939.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_GWF1">Gibbs</persName> added that in view of the
                    present situation in Europe he would have nothing more to do with the
                    project.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GJC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Joseph C. Green</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
